{{Use Pakistani English|date=May 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}} {{Infobox university | name =Federal Urdu University of Arts, Science and Technology | native_name = وفاقی جامعہ اردو | mottoeng = ''Inspiring Achievement'' | established ={{Start date|1949}} | closed = <!-- {{End date|YYYY}} --> | type =[[Public university|Public]] | affiliation = | endowment = | budget = | rector = | officer_in_charge = | chairman = | chancellor =[[President of Pakistan]] | president = | vice-president = | superintendent = | provost = | vice_chancellor = Prof. Dr. S. Altaf Hussain<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fuuast.edu.pk/university-organization/|title=University Organization – FUUAST|website=fuuast.edu.pk}}</ref> | dean = Professor Dr. Rubina Mushtaq, Professor Dr. Muhammad Zia-ud-Din, Professor Dr. Masood Mashkoor Siddiqui, Dr. Mohammad Ashraf Khurram | director = | head_label =Registrar | head =Mr. Afzaal Ahmed | academic_staff =450 | administrative_staff = | students =~13,500 | undergrad = | postgrad = | doctoral = | other = | city =[[Karachi]], [[Islamabad]] | state = | province = | country =[[Pakistan]]{{flagicon|Pakistan}} | campus =[[Residential college|Residential]] | former_names =Urdu College | colours ={{color box|#CC0000}}{{color box|#009900}}{{color box|#FAEBD7}} | sports = | nickname ='''FUUAST''' | mascot = | website = {{URL|fuuast.edu.pk}}, {{URL|fuuastisb.edu.pk}} | logo = | footnotes = | image_name =Federal Urdu University.png | coor ={{Coord|24.9120|N|67.0907|E|type:edu_region:PK|display=inline,title}} | colors =[[Red]], [[green]], [[antique white]] | affiliations =[[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)]], [[Pakistan Engineering Council]], [[Pakistan Bar Council]], [[Pharmacy Council of Pakistan]], [[National Council for Homeopathy]] }}
The '''Federal Urdu University of Arts, Science and Technology''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|وفاقی جامعہ اردو}}}}; alternatively known as '''FUUAST''') is a [[public university]] primarily located in the residential [[Gulshan Town]] and [[Saddar]] of [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]].<ref name="Google maps">{{cite web|last=Google maps|title=Address of Federal Urdu University|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?gs_rn=26&gs_ri=psy-ab&cp=10&gs_id=1x&xhr=t&q=federal+urdu+university&bav=on.2,or.r_qf.&bvm=bv.52164340,d.cGE&biw=1024&bih=566&dpr=1&um=1&ie=UTF-8&hl=en&sa=N&tab=wl||publisher=Google maps|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> The university has two satellite campuses; the central campus is located in [[Islamabad]] while the secondary campus is located in [[Karachi]].<ref name=PakistanEconomist/>
The university offers wide range of academic programs in [[undergraduate]] and [[post-graduate]]. The university is noted for its engaging research in [[fine arts]], languages, engineering, social sciences and philosophy.<ref name=PakistanEconomist>{{cite web| author=Amanullah Bashar| title=Urdu University: A Gift Of The Present Government| publisher=Pakistan Economist (magazine)|date=6 October 2006 | url=http://www.pakistaneconomist.com/issue2002/issue39/etc4.htm| accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> With an tentative approximated of ~13,500 enrolled students currently attending the university, it is one of the largest institution in the country and is one of the top university in "general category" ranked by the [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)]].<ref name="Higher Education Commission">{{cite web|last=Government of Pakistan |first=HEC |title=Pakistan's Higher Education Commission's List of University rankings |url=http://www.hec.gov.pk/INSIDEHEC/DIVISIONS/QALI/OTHERS/RANKINGOFUNIVERSITIES/Pages/CategoryWise.aspx |work=Government of Pakistan website|publisher=Higher Education Commission |accessdate=11 May 2018|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525073744/http://www.hec.gov.pk/InsideHEC/Divisions/QALI/Others/RankingofUniversities/Pages/CategoryWise.aspx |archivedate=25 May 2013 |df= }}</ref>
The Federal Urdu University holds a unique distinction of being as one of the few institutions of higher learning in languages and maintains a distinguish reputation for conducting scientific research towards the advancement of [[languages]], [[engineering]], [[philosophy]], [[natural sciences|natural]], [[medical science|medical]] and [[social sciences]].<ref name="FUU Press">{{cite web|last=FUU Press|title=Introduction of FUU|url=http://www.fuuast.edu.pk/history|publisher=FUU Press|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> In addition, the university is also known for its financial affordability while engaged in offering an international standard scientific research and development in various academic mulch-disciplines.<ref name="FUU Press"/>
==History== Urdu College was first established by Baba-e-Urdu Maulvi Abdul Haq in 1949.<ref name=PakistanEconomist/> Then this college was given the status of a University in 2002. The Federal Urdu University was established on 13 November 2002 by presidential order and is the first university in Pakistan to teach primarily in the [[Urdu language]]. It was established by merging the Federal Urdu Arts College and the Federal Urdu Science College, both in Karachi. President [[Pervez Musharraf]] was the university's first chancellor. In 2018, [[President of Pakistan]], [[Mamnoon Hussain]] and Prof. Dr. S. Altaf Hussain are the chancellor and vice-chancellor of the university respectively.<ref name=PakistanEconomist/>
==Campuses and departments== {{Location map+ | Karachi | width = 350 | caption = Location of Abdul Haq Campus and Gulshan Campus within Karachi. | places
{{Location map~ | Karachi | label = Gulshan | position = right | background = white | marksize = 11 | link = | lat_deg = 24.9120 | lon_deg = 67.0907 }} {{Location map~ | Karachi | label = Abdul Haq | position = right | background = white | marksize = 11 | link = | lat_deg = 24.8612 | lon_deg = 67.0097 }} }}
The Federal Urdu University comprises three campuses and a number of departments: *''Abdul Haq Campus'' at Baba-e-Urdu Road, Karachi (previously known as ''Federal Urdu Arts College'')<ref name=PakistanEconomist/> *''Gulshan Campus'' at the University Road, Gulshan-e-Iqbal, Karachi (previously known as ''Federal Urdu Science College'')<ref name=PakistanEconomist/> *''Islamabad campus'', Sector G-7/1, near Zero point, Islamabad (established in 2003)
