{{member|name=[[Robert Baden-Powell, 1st Baron Baden-Powell|Robert Stephenson Smyth Baden-Powell]] / 1st Baronet Baden-Powell of Bentley / 1st Baron Baden-Powell of [[Gilwell Park|Gilwell]] (Robert Stephenson Smyth Powell)|nota=British Army scout, intelligence officer,<ref>With his brother Baden Fletcher Smyth Baden-Powell (1860-1937), went spying in Russia, got detained, and escaped.</ref> and general. Founder of the [[Scouting|Scout Movement]] and [[The Scout Association]].<ref>The Scout Movement is the most widespread associated network of outdoor adventure-based education implementers. There are several international federations within the Movement, the largest of which is the [[World Organization of the Scout Movement]] with headquarters in Genève, Switzerland.</ref><ref>Aside from Scouting affiliates, there also have been organizations which sprouted out and away from the root Scout idea.[http://www.troop97.net/scout_like.htm]</ref> Organised Scout Huts (emulating YMCA Huts) for soldiers' R&R in WW2.<ref>While organizing Scout Huts, he was suspected, probably erroneously, of involvement in intelligence work.</ref> [[1st World Scout Jamboree|"Chief Scout of the World"]]. Many works include books on military scouting ([[reconnaissance]]) and youth Scouting, including ''[[Scouting for Boys]]'', [[List of best-selling books|bestseller]] of the 20th century, and ''[[Rovering to Success]]''. East Twin and West Twin peaks in the [[San Gabriel Mountains]] have been renamed [[Mount Baden-Powell]] and [[Mount Burnham]] after the two friends.||ref=<ref>Many biographies of Baden-Powell have been written. Three of the most important accounts of the founding of the Scout Movement are Colin Walker's ''The Dawn of the World Scout Movement'' (Write Books), Walker's ''Brownsea: BP's Acorn'' (Write Books), and Scott & Murphy's ''The Scouting Party'' (Irving, Texas: Red Honor Press, 2010 [http://thescoutingparty.com]).</ref>}}
