{{member|name=[[William Hillcourt]] / Green Bar Bill (Vilhelm Hans Bjerregaard Jensen)|nota=Boy Scout; Scoutmaster; Scouting professional. Served in various positions in the Boy Scouts of America. Authored many books and articles on Scouting, outdoor activities, and Scout skills, including the first ''Scout Fieldbook'' and three editions of the ''[[Boy Scout Handbook]]'' of the BSA. Endeavored to maintain the outdoor orientation of US Boy Scouting.[http://scoutingrediscovered.com/scoutcraft/how-scouting-was-saved-in-79] Recipient of the [[Bronze Wolf Award|Bronze Wolf]] and the [[Silver Buffalo Award|Silver Buffalo]].<ref>Hillcourt was a trainee at the first [[Wood Badge (Boy Scouts of America)|Wood Badge]] course in the USA (ran by [[J. S. Wilson|John Skinner Wilson]]), 1936, and served as Senior Patrol Leader at the second course some days later. He organized Wood Badge as a regular BSA program in 1948, serving as the first Course Leader. As the national director of training (a.k.a. the Deputy [[Gilwell Park|Gilwell]] Camp Chief), he wore five [[Wood Badge#Beads|Wood Badge beads]].</ref> |ref=<ref>[http://www.trussel.com/prehist/crump/hillcour.htm Block, Nelson, "William Hillcourt: Scoutmaster to the World", ''The Journal of Scouting History''.]</ref>}}
